00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,409
3.

2
00:00:01,760 --> 00:00:02,929
It's no use.

3
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:05,409
I'm too old or too young.

4
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:14,689
Age excusitis, the failure disease of never being the right age, comes in two easily identifiable forms,

5
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:19,250
the I'm-too-old variety and the I'm-too-young brand.

6
00:00:19,760 --> 00:00:26,290
You've heard hundreds of people of all ages explain their mediocre performance in life something like this.

7
00:00:26,880 --> 00:00:30,770
I'm too old, or too young, to break in now.

8
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:36,850
I can't do what I want to do or am capable of doing because of my age handicap.

9
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:44,770
Really, it's surprising how few people feel they are just right, age-wise, and it's unfortunate.

10
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:50,530
This excuse has closed the door of real opportunity to thousands of individuals.

11
00:00:50,800 --> 00:00:55,169
They think their age is wrong, so they don't even bother to try.

12
00:00:55,919 --> 00:01:01,330
The I'm-too-old variety is the most common form of age excusitis.

13
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:04,449
This disease is spread in subtle ways.

14
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:13,570
TV fiction is produced about the big executive who lost his job because of a merger and can't find another because he's too old.

15
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:18,209
Mr. Executive looks for months to find another job, but he can't,

16
00:01:18,320 --> 00:01:26,290
and in the end, after contemplating suicide for a while, he decides to rationalize that it's nice to be on the shelf.

17
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:32,130
Plays and magazine articles on the topic, why you are washed up at 40,

18
00:01:32,159 --> 00:01:40,530
are popular, not because they represent true facts, but because they appeal to many worried minds looking for an excuse.

19
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,729
How to handle age excusitis.

20
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:48,850
Ajexcusitis can be cured.

21
00:01:49,040 --> 00:02:00,449
A few years ago, while I was conducting a sales training program, I discovered a good serum that both cures this disease and vaccinates you so you won't get it in the first place.

22
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:04,610
In that training program, there was a trainee named Cecil.

23
00:02:04,720 --> 00:02:11,490
Cecil, who was 40, wanted to shift over to set himself up as a manufacturer's representative,

24
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:13,490
but he thought he was too old.

25
00:02:13,919 --> 00:02:19,570
After all," he explained, I'd have to start from scratch, and I'm too old for that now.

26
00:02:19,679 --> 00:02:20,850
I'm forty.

27
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:25,890
I'd talked with Cecil several times about his old age problem.

28
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:32,209
I used the old medicine, you're only as old as you feel, but I found I was getting nowhere.

29
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:36,370
Too often people retort with, but I do feel old.

30
00:02:37,120 --> 00:02:40,050
And finally, I discovered a method that worked.

31
00:02:40,320 --> 00:02:44,050
One day, after a training session, I tried it on Cecil.

32
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:48,209
I said, Cecil, when does a man's productive life begin?

33
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:53,890
He thought a couple of seconds and answered, oh, when he's about twenty, I guess.

34
00:02:54,480 --> 00:02:56,130
Okay, I said.

35
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:59,650
Now, when does a man's productive life end?

36
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:05,169
Cecil answered, well, if he stays in good shape and likes his work.

37
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:11,570
I guess a man is still pretty useful when he's seventy or so." "'All right,' I said.

38
00:03:11,570 --> 00:03:15,570
"'A lot of folks are highly productive after they reach seventy.

39
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:18,130
But let's agree with what you've just said.

40
00:03:18,320 --> 00:03:22,050
A man's productive years stretch from twenty to seventy.

41
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:27,969
That's fifty years in between, or half a century.' "'Cecil,' I said.

42
00:03:27,969 --> 00:03:29,250
"'You're forty.

43
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:34,530
How many years of productive life have you spent?' "'Twenty,' he answered.

44
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:36,929
And how many have you left?

45
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:39,570
Thirty, he replied.

46
00:03:40,080 --> 00:03:44,290
In other words, Cecil, you haven't even reached the halfway point.

47
00:03:44,480 --> 00:03:48,370
You've used up only 40% of your productive years.

48
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:52,610
I looked at Cecil and realized he'd gotten the point.

49
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:55,570
He was cured of age excusitis.

50
00:03:55,760 --> 00:04:00,370
Cecil saw he still had many opportunity-filled years left.

51
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:05,250
He switched from thinking, I'm already old, to, I'm still young.

